        "disaster_description": "On 29 December 2018, Tropical Depression 'Usman' made landfall in the vicinity of Borongan, Eastern Samar, at 6:00 AM, and weakened into a low pressure area (LPA). Over 4,300 persons were affected in 5 provinces. As of 30 December, 2018, at least 128,000 people were affected in 26 provinces in Regions V, VIII, CALABARZON, and MIMAROPA. More than 13,000 people are staying in 112 evacuation centers. Rescue teams in the Philippines searched for dozens of missing residents after Cyclone Usman swept through the Southeast Asian archipelago, leaving 22 people dead. The tropical storm brought heavy rain to the Bicol and Eastern Visayas regions, causing massive flooding and landslides. At least 16 people died in Bicol while six others were killed in Eastern Visayas. Tropical Depression Usman has caused flood and landslides affecting around 130,000 persons from Regions IV-A (Calabarzon), IV-B (Mimaropa), V (Bicol), and VIII (Eastern Visayas). According to the National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council (NDRRMC), 68 have died and 19 are still missing. Four provinces in Region V (Bicol) and 8 municipalities in Oriental Mindoro have been placed under state of calamity. Multiple landslides and widespread flooding caused by Tropical Depression Usman have resulted in over 120 deaths. More than 680,000 people across 14 provinces have been affected by the storm. At the peak, some 456,000 people were displaced with 1,600 homes reported destroyed and 8,800 damaged. Estimated agricultural losses continue to rise, reaching PHP1 billion (US$ 18 million), with nearly 37,000 farmers and fisherfolk affected. As of 10 January, over 1,900 homes are destroyed and more than 15,000 are damaged. The Department of Education reports that over 14,000 learners have been affected. Most of the schools in Buhi, Camarines Sur, were submerged in floodwaters, which damaged desks, textbooks and school supplies. Agricultural losses are approaching PHP2 billion (US$37 million), with over 56,000 farmers and fisherfolk affected. More than 23,000 metric tons of rice, corn and high-value crops and over 54,000 hectares of farmland are estimated to have been affected. As of 20 January, more than one million people were affected by TD Usman. Over 8,200 people are displaced. At least 2,800 people are taking shelter in 23 evacuation centers. A total of 28 dead are confirmed. As of 30 January, 18 evacuation shelters remain open to serve at least 2,500 people affected by TD Usman in Calabarzon, Mimaropa, Region V and Region VIII.",
        "interventions": "Some affected provinces have asked for public donations. P9.2 million ($1.8 million) in assistance has been provided by local authorities, NGOs and DSWD. Evacuation centres are beginning to close as people return to their homes: from a peak of 536 shelters, 117 remain open, hosting 57,300 people. Another 83,500 people have already left evacuation centres. The number of people staying with relatives or friends is also declining, from a peak of 220,800 to 158,200.",
        "affected_countries": ["Philippines"],
        "sources": ["Govt. of Philippines", "Deutsche Welle", "ECHO", "OCHA", "Department of Social Welfare and Development (DSWD)", "Department of Education", "Department of Agriculture", "United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO)"],
