https://reliefweb.int/disaster/2013-0000:
{
    "https://reliefweb.int/disaster/2013-000034-mdg": {
        "disaster_title": "Madagascar: Locusts - Mar 2013",
        "disaster_type": ["Locust Plague"],
        "date": "Mar 2013",
        "disaster_description": "The plague of the Malagasy Migratory Locust began in April 2012 in Madagascar, in a context where food insecurity and malnutrition rates were already high. Given the extent of the plague, it was estimated that the food security of about 13 million people (60 percent of the population) could be affected in the absence of large-scale locust control operations. To cope with this dire situation, in December 2012, the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development of Madagascar and the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations developed a Three-year Programme (2013–2016) in response to the locust plague. Donor response has been timely and positive. The first locust campaign was fully funded and successfully implemented. The specific objective of the campaign, aimed at halting the dynamics of the locust plague while protecting crops and pastures, was achieved. Following surveys carried out on more than 30 million ha, the locust populations in an area exceeding 1.2 million ha were controlled, without any incident affecting human health or the environment and without causing significant damage to the major rice baskets. In order to sustain the results achieved during the first campaign, it is essential to support the decline of the locust plague during the 2014/15 campaign and return, in 2016, to a locust recession situation (overall objective of the Three-year Programme), thus putting an end to the locust crises’ cycle and avoiding further deterioration of the significant food insecurity situation.",
        "interventions": "The Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development of Madagascar and the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations developed a Three-year Programme (2013–2016) in response to the locust plague. The first locust campaign was fully funded and successfully implemented. Surveys were carried out on more than 30 million ha, and locust populations in an area exceeding 1.2 million ha were controlled. The decline of the invasion was achieved during the 2014/15 campaign. The third and final campaign (2015/16) aimed to treat 350,000 hectares to return to a remission situation. Damage caused by locusts to crops and pastures in 2016 was negligible at the national level.",
        "affected_countries": ["Madagascar"],
        "sources": ["FAO"],
        "language": "English, French"
    }
}

