https://reliefweb.int/disaster/ep-2024-0:
{
    "https://reliefweb.int/disaster/ep-2024-000002-zmb": {
        "disaster_title": "Zambia: Cholera Outbreak - Oct 2023",
        "disaster_type": ["Epidemic"],
        "date": "October 2023",
        "disaster_description": "A cholera outbreak which was first reported in October 2023 has seen a dramatic increase in transmission since mid-December. The country has now recorded a cumulative 8,276 cases and 333 deaths, with 446 new cases and 23 deaths in the past 24 hours according to a daily update from the Ministry of Health resulting in a case fatality rate of 4%. Thirty-one percent of the cases are in children under five years old. The outbreak initially emerged in peri-urban areas of Lusaka Province, which still has the most cases. But due to the high rate of transmission, the disease is now affecting people across multiple geographical areas. Since the start of the current cholera outbreak, nine out of the ten provinces have reported cases of cholera with seven provinces confirming cholera outbreaks. Cumulatively this year, as of 11 February 2024, there have been 18,519 reported cases and 652 deaths (CFR = 3.5%). In week 06/2024, new cases decreased by 47.2% from 1,777 in the previous week to 938 new cases. New deaths decreased by 50.0% from 46 deaths in the previous week to 23. All the 10 provinces are reporting cases. The total number of districts reporting case are 70. The highest level of government response has been activated and coordinated by Disaster Management and Mitigation Unit (DMMU) under the office of the Vice President. The most affected areas are all the sub-districts in Lusaka District (especially the peri-urban), fishing areas in Luangwa district, sewage compound in Chongwe district using water from the wells. Cases and deaths are now on the increase in the Copperbelt province with a 9% and 50% respectively compared to the previous week. Cumulatively this year, as of 10 March 2024, there have been 21,330 reported cases and 704 deaths (CFR = 3.3%). In week 10 of 2024, new cases decreased by 5.1% from 592 in the previous week to 562. New deaths also decreased by 81.8% from 11 deaths in the previous week to two. All the 10 provinces are reporting cases. The total number of districts reporting case are 70. The current cholera outbreak started with Lusaka Province confirming cases in the cholera-prone areas (peri-urban). From October 2023 to 6 May, 2024, nine provinces have reported cases of cholera with seven provinces confirming cholera outbreaks. A total of 40 districts have confirmed local transmission. Cumulative cases stand at 23,221 with 740 deaths (CFR 3.2%).",
        "interventions": "The highest level of government response has been activated and coordinated by Disaster Management and Mitigation Unit (DMMU) under the office of the Vice President.",
        "affected_countries": ["Zambia"],
        "sources": ["IFRC", "WHO"],
        "language": "English"
    }
}

