        "disaster_description": "Indian Meteorological Department (IMD) issues active monsoon warning with heavy to very heavy rainfall warning over Northwest, East & Northeast India during next 4-5 days. In Assam, as per the Assam State Disaster Management Authority (ASDMA) report, major river Brahmaputra is flowing above the flood level due to heavy rain. 19 districts are affected with floods, with more than 640,000 population affected. Heavy rainfall, thunderstorms and lightning have affected north-western India, in particular the Uttar Pradesh state, causing severe weather-related incidents that have resulted in casualties and damage. Cloudburst on July 25 causes heavy rainfall and flooding across parts of India, including Maharashtra, Gujarat, Andhra Pradesh, and Himachal Pradesh. On 30 July, a series of landslides triggered by the monsoon rainfall occurred in the Wayanad district (Kerala state, southern India) and resulted in casualties and damage. The humanitarian impact is increasing after a series of landslides triggered by the monsoon rainfall that occurred in the Wayanad district (Kerala state, southern India) on 30 July. On 31 July-1 August, heavy rainfall and strong winds affected three districts (Shimla, Mandi, and Kullu) of Himachal Pradesh state (northern India) causing severe weather-related incidents and triggering flash-floods that resulted in casualties and damage.",
