        "disaster_description": "On 11-13 April, severe flooding and landslides caused by heavy rainfall affected southern and south-eastern South Africa, particularly the Provinces of KwaZulu-Natal and Eastern Cape. According to national authorities, 443 people died in KwaZulu-Natal and over 40,000 are missing. More than 40,000 people have been displaced, while nearly 4,000 houses were destroyed and more than 8,000 others were damaged, mostly across Durban City and its surrounding areas. A National State of Disaster has been declared in response to the floods and landslides, and rescue teams have been deployed to the affected areas to provide humanitarian assistance to those most affected. The International Disaster Charter 755 was activated for South Africa. Severe flooding and landslides caused by heavy rainfall on 11-13 April caused the death of 448 people, displaced over 40,000 people and completely destroyed over 12,000 houses in the south-east part of South Africa. It also severely damaged infrastructures: roads, health centres, schools.",
        "interventions": "A National State of Disaster has been declared. Rescue teams have been deployed to provide humanitarian assistance. The International Disaster Charter 755 was activated. The KwaZulu-Natal Provincial Government is planning to set up 4,396 temporary accommodation sites. The government has reprioritised R1 billion towards disaster relief interventions, but the province needs more than R1.9 billion to complete the work. An integrated approach involving three spheres of government is assisting to ensure speed and efficiency in the interventions. The government is working to identify suitable land to house new settlements for the displaced.",
