    "https://reliefweb.int/disaster/fl-2019-000153-cod": {
        "disaster_title": "DR Congo: Floods - Oct 2019",
        "disaster_type": ["Flood"],
        "date": "2019-10",
        "disaster_description": "Several regions of [DRC] have been affected by flooding, following intense rain since mid October. The worst hit areas are Zongo and Libenge towns (Sud-Ubangi Province, north-western DRC), where the river Ubangui breached its banks and flood waters have yet to recede. One person died in Zongo and 36,800 people are homeless. In Sud-Ubangi province, media report 14,200 houses damaged, 12 schools, 21 bridges, 48 public buildings and wide areas of crops. Floods since October have affected more than 10,000 people in Dungu locality in Haut Uele province in north-east DRC. The flood-affected people are being hosted by other families. Around 600 under 5 children are among those affected by floods, according to the local Red Cross. The floods have destroyed hundreds of farms, raising fears of food shortages. Since the end of October, heavy rains caused flooding in Isangi territory, eastern Ituri province, affecting 45 villages and forcing 18,000 people to flee inundated areas. No humanitarian response has been provided yet and those affected are in dire need of shelter, household items, water and healthcare. Heavy rainfall affected several parts of the country (particularly the capital Kinshasa) on 25-26 November causing floods and triggering landslides, displacing 400,000 people. According to media reports, as of 28 November, at least 41 people died in Kinshasa City area, most of them because of a landslide. In addition, more than 300 houses have been flooded in Lemba Municipality (Kinshasa District) and the bridge linking the Municipalities of Lemba and Ngaba collapsed. Education authorities in Tshopo province have identified at least 64 schools affected by floods. These school structures are either flooded or have collapsed; textbooks, school equipment and desks are completely lost. As a result, some 12,300 students are deprived of access to education. 10 of the 17 health zones in Tshopo province are affected by floods, affecting over 133,000 people in 131 villages. Many people are being hosted by other families. In the neighbouring provinces of Bas-Uélé and Haut-Uélé, nearly 30,000 people are also affected by floods. In the DRC, government figures in mid-December reported over 923,000 people affected by the floods. These populations are subject to severe deprivations as a result of the disaster. Many have partially or completely lost their homes and property, as well as livelihoods, crops and agricultural land. The displaced population has relocated into homes of other families, public places (schools) or makeshift shelters, some of which are also affected by the floods.",
        "interventions": "Rescue and emergency teams have been deployed to help the affected people. On 16 December, the European Union announced the allocation of one million euros to assist people affected by floods and torrential rains across the country.",
        "affected_countries": ["Democratic Republic of the Congo"],
        "sources": ["ECHO", "OCHA", "IFRC"],
        "language": "English"
    }
}

https://reliefweb.int/disaster/fl-2017-0:
{
    "https://reliefweb.int/disaster/fl-2017-000075-chn": {
        "disaster_title": "China: Floods and Landslides - Jun 2017",
        "disaster_type": ["Flood", "Landslide", "Tropical Storm", "Typhoon"],
        "date": "2017-06-27",
        "disaster_description": "Over the past week, heavy rains in southern China caused severe floods and landslides affecting over 7.3 million people. A massive landslide in Xinmo village (Sichuan province), left at least 10 people dead and nearly 100 people still missing. Heavy rainfall is forecasted in the coming days which could trigger additional landslides. Heavy rains in the past few days have led to widespread flooding in southern China, killing over 15 and forcing the evacuation of tens and thousands of people. On July 3, 2017, China issued a grade-IV emergency response for rain and floods that have left 16 dead and 10 missing in Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region. Over 92,000 residents have been relocated. The disaster has caused around 2.9 billion yuan in direct economic losses. Thousands are battling floods in various provinces along the Yangtze River. In Hunan province, the Xiangjian River reached a record 39.51 meters on July 3, beating the previous record of 39.18 set by a flood in 1998. Floods have inundated houses, uprooted trees, damaged cars and sabotaged roads in Changsha, capital of Hunan. Around 16,000 people are on high alert for flooding in neighboring Hubei while 28,100 people are battling against floods in eastern Jiangxi Province. Natural disasters killed 204 people in China in the first six months of 2017, with floods and geological hazards accounting for 134 of these deaths. Since 29 July, flash floods in Shaanxi Province have caused 10 deaths and prompted the evacuation of an estimated 76,800 people. Parts of Qinghai, Gansu and Yunnan provinces were also affected by localized flash floods, where authorities issued landslide warnings. On 27 August, Tropical Storm Pakhar made landfall in China, bringing high winds and rain to Hong Kong and Macau just days after Typhoon Hato caused serious flooding and damage in the same areas. Between 20 August and 2 September, more than 28,000 people were evacuated in Fujian province due to the effects of Typhoon Hato and Tropical Storm Mawar. More than 17,000 people were evacuated in the south-west provinces of Chongqing, Guizhou, Sichuan and Yunnan following heavy rains that triggered flooding and landslides. Around 800 people were evacuated in the north-west provinces of Qinghai and Shaanxi following heavy rains and landslides. As of 9 October, 23 people have died due to heavy rain that started on 1 October. Storms have forced the evacuation of nearly 34,000 people in Chongqing Municipality and the provinces of Anhui, Henan, Hubei, Sichuan and Shaanxi. More than 5,200 houses collapsed and over 24,000 were damaged. Direct economic losses are estimated at 3.26 billion yuan. As of 12 October, 5 people have been killed and approximately 26,700 people evacuated due to torrential rain in Hubei Province. More than 8,500 homes were destroyed. Direct economic losses are estimated at approximately 4 billion yuan. On 16 October, Typhoon Khanun made landfall in Xuwen county, Guangdong Province, in southern China. More than 368,000 people within heavily affected areas of the province, and at least 38,200 tourists, had been relocated in advance of the typhoon. Guangdong, and neighbouring provinces Fujian and Hainan, experienced disruption to construction, schooling, maritime and transportation operations. On November 8, heavy downpours forced the evacuation of over 11,000 people in southern China's Hainanan province. In the city of Wanning, over 78 villages were flooded, a highway section was inundated, and all schools were suspended.",
        "interventions": "The Government has deployed rescue teams to the affected areas. Red Cross Emergency Response Teams are providing relief goods and support to the search and rescue operations. The Chinese government has set aside a total of 1.88 billion yuan (276.8 million US dollars) to aid disaster relief in 20 provinces and regions. The Ministry of Finance and the Ministry of Civil Affairs have allocated 100 million yuan (about 15 million US dollars) for flood relief operations. Fire fighters, border patrol, and armed police have been deployed for rescue operations.",
        "affected_countries": ["China"],
        "sources": ["OCHA", "Xinhua", "IDMC"],
        "language": "English"
    }
}

