    "https://reliefweb.int/disaster/fl-2020-000210-vnm": {
        "disaster_title": "Viet Nam: Floods and Landslides - Sep 2020",
        "disaster_type": ["Flood", "Landslide", "Tropical Cyclone", "Typhoon"],
        "date": "September 2020",
        "disaster_description": "Tropical Cyclone NOUL made landfall in Viet Nam over the coastal area between Dong Ha and Hue cities (Thua Thien Hue Province) on 18 September, as a tropical storm. More than 500,000 people were evacuated in the central provinces of Vietnam. TC Noul caused damage to the Central provinces of Vietnam, with 4 provinces evacuating around 16,391 households or about 54,215 people. Houses were severely affected, and the agriculture sector suffered due to heavy rain following the storm. There were 6 fatalities and 112 injured, with severe damage to infrastructure. Continued heavy rain led to warnings of flash floods. Landslides triggered by flash floods occurred in the mountainous districts of Quang Nam Province, damaging houses, schools, roads, and bridges, leaving many communities isolated. Heavy rain affected northern Vietnam, causing floods, landslides, casualties, and damage. Torrential rains submerged and cut off many areas in central Viet Nam, leading to evacuations. The Vietnam Disaster Management Authority reported severe flooding and landslides, with numerous fatalities, missing persons, and displaced people. Typhoon MOLAVE and other storms exacerbated the situation, causing further evacuations, damage, and casualties. Persistent heavy rains, widespread flooding, and landslides triggered by a series of storms and typhoons since early October left more than 270,000 houses flooded and damaged more than 37,500 houses in central Vietnam. Typhoon GONI and Tropical Storm ETAU also contributed to the devastation.",
        "interventions": "Evacuations of hundreds of thousands of people were conducted. Rescue teams accessed isolated areas by boats to supply food and evacuate vulnerable individuals. The Vietnam Disaster Management Authority and provincial authorities deployed rescue teams and evacuated vulnerable people. The army mobilized troops and vehicles for search and rescue missions. Local authorities planned evacuations and reinforced sea dikes. Humanitarian assistance was prioritized for vulnerable populations.",
        "affected_countries": ["Viet Nam"],
        "sources": ["ECHO", "OCHA", "UNCT Viet Nam", "AHA Centre", "UNICEF"],
        "language": "English"
    }
}

