    }
}

https://reliefweb.int/disaster/ls-2016-0:
{
    "https://reliefweb.int/disaster/ls-2016-000051-idn": {
        "disaster_title": "Indonesia: Floods and Landslides - May 2016",
        "disaster_type": ["Flood", "Landslide"],
        "date": "May 2016",
        "disaster_description": "Between 10 to 13 May, floods and flash floods occurred in the provinces of South, West and Central Kalimantan, Bengkulu and Gorontalo. The incidents flooded 3,550 houses for several days. In Kotabaru District (South Kalimantan), flash floods killed three people with one still missing. The monsoon season in Indonesia typically runs from November to March – the amount of rainfall and intensity during the past week is unusual at this time of year. Since 25 May, some 2,400 houses were flooded for several days in South Sulawesi, West Java and Banten provinces. There were no reported casualties or major damage. In another incident, flash floods, triggered by heavy rainfall on 22 May, killed six people in Subang District, West Java. An estimated 390 people remain displaced in IDP sites. From 5 to 9 June, flooding triggered by high tides and heavy rainfall occurred across 12 provinces in Sumatra, Java, Bali and Nusa Tenggara. At least 5,900 houses and temporary stalls were damaged and more than 30,000 houses were flooded. From 17 to 20 June, heavy rainfall and high tide warnings were issued for parts of Sumatra, Java, Bali, and East Nusa Tenggara. In Central Java province, floods and landslides caused 35 deaths while 25 are still missing. At least 100 houses were damaged. Flooding also occurred in West Sumatra province, causing one death. Flooding and landslides in Central Java province caused 59 deaths, with four people still missing. In Purworejo, the worst affected district, about 350 people remain displaced. In North Sulawesi province, flooding and landslides also caused five deaths and damaged over 200 houses. On 16 July, prolonged and heavy rainfall triggered flooding in North Konawe district, North Sulawesi province. Up to 2.5 metres of flood water submerged 730 houses and displaced some 1,350 people. On 19 July, at least 100 houses were inundated in Sorong city, West Papua province as flash floods swept through the area. From 01-07 August, 45 houses were flooded in Ende, East Nusa Tenggara Province. From 08-14 August, floods inundated an estimated 250 houses in Ciamis, in West Java Province. From 15-21 August, widespread landslides affected 386 families and damaged rice fields and infrastructure in the district of Sukabumi, in West Java. Heavy rains triggered floods and flash floods in several districts in East Java Province. From 22 - 28 August, torrential rain caused heavy flooding in Jakarta, impacting nearly 33,000 people. Floods also affected parts of Aceh province. From 29 August - 4 September, floods affected 756 people in Cianjur, West Java Province, while 600 people were evacuated due to flooding in Deli Serdang, North Sumatra Province. A landslide in Pontianak, the capital of West Kalimantan province, damaged 57 homes. A La Niña weather event will likely start in August or September 2016 and will continue into the last quarter of 2016, causing wetter than normal weather conditions. Flash floods in Garut, West Java on 21 September caused 33 deaths, with 20 people still missing and over 6,000 people temporarily displaced. Flooding was also reported in West Lombok, West Nusa Tenggara and Sampang, East Java on 24 and 25 September. From 03 - 09 October, heavy rains triggered floods and landslides in Banjar City, West Java Province. Following days of torrential rainfall and high tides, at least 1,000 houses were flooded in coastal areas of Palopo City, South Sulawesi province on 21 and 22 October. Heavy rain caused flooding in parts of the central and western areas of the country in the period including 24-25 October. Over 24 hours during 25-26 October, approximately 131 mm of rain was recorded in Gorontalo city, in Gorontalo province on Sulawesi Island. Between 29 and 31 October, 5,000 houses were flooded in Gorontalo and West Java provinces, affecting about 15,700 people and killing three children.",
        "interventions": "Local governments provided assistance to the affected people. The local government declared an emergency response for a week and provided basic relief assistance. Local disaster management authorities provided assistance to the affected communities. Government agencies, the Red Cross, NGOs and the private sector are providing clean water, food, NFIs, shelter and rehabilitating critical infrastructure. Local authorities provided relief to the affected people. Local governments provided temporary shelter, food, water and health services to the affected people.",
        "affected_countries": ["Indonesia"],
        "sources": ["OCHA", "ASEAN", "WFP", "Govt. of Indonesia", "ECHO"],
        "language": "English"
    }
}

