        "disaster_title": "Pacific: Drought - May 2022",
        "disaster_type": ["Drought"],
        "date": "2022-06-11",
        "disaster_description": "On 11 June, the Kiribati Government declared a State of Disaster due to drought. According to government sources, the entire country (some 120,000 people) has been affected - with the most critical situation to be reported on the island of Tarawa. The drought in Kiribati continues to worsen, with increasing challenges and threats in terms of water contamination, brackish water, water accessibility and water availability. La Niña conditions were observed in the equatorial Pacific starting in November 2021. Since then, Kiribati, Tuvalu, Tokelau, and Nauru have experienced high water stress because of low rainfall and dry conditions. This situation is expected to persist as La Niña is predicted to continue until the last quarter of 2022.",
        "interventions": "The immediate response is to focus on 50,000 of the most affected people, including those living on South Tarawa and the outer islands. They will be provided with WASH and hygiene kits from prepositioned stocks and subsequently with further humanitarian relief supplies from warehouses in Suva, Fiji, and Brisbane, Australia. This follows an initial assistance of 100 solar distillation units for outer communities. The Pacific Humanitarian Team is working closely with Government counterparts and partners on the ground to further assess the situation and to provide support to the Government-led response. Response efforts by Government include the technical assessments for water quality and the provision of safe drinking water to the general population. In Tuvalu, the Government has developed their drought response plan and have formally asked the UN for support, which involves provision of reverse osmosis (RO) machines to generate fresh water in critical areas and early anticipatory actions.",
        "affected_countries": ["Kiribati", "Tuvalu"],
        "sources": ["OCHA", "UNICEF"],
        "language": "English"
    }
}

