https://reliefweb.int/disaster/ep-2016-0:
{
    "https://reliefweb.int/disaster/ep-2016-000053-som": {
        "disaster_title": "Somalia: Cholera Outbreak - Apr 2016",
        "disaster_type": ["Epidemic", "Cholera"],
        "date": "April 2016",
        "disaster_description": "Humanitarian partners have stepped up response to the outbreak...Projections of 15,000 severe and 60,000 moderate cases over the coming months have led to plans for a significant and rapid scale up of the response. To help stabilize and contain the outbreak, the CERF rapid response grant of $2 million will strengthen and complement response activities already underway by WASH and Health partners. Since the beginning of 2016, a total of 14165 cases of AWD and 497 deaths have been reported in different parts of Somalia. Of these 47.7% are female while 57.9% are children below 5 years. There has been a gradual reduction in number of cases from the peak 1,853 cases and 187 deaths (CFR 10.0%) in week 15 to 194 cases and 0 death in week 46. Drought conditions have increased the spread of epidemic-prone diseases such as acute watery diarrhoea, cholera and measles. In the first 7 weeks of 2017, more than 6000 cases and 65 deaths by acute watery diarrhoea/ cholera were reported. The AWD/cholera epidemic in Hiraan, Nugal, Mudug and Bari and Banadir region has been controlled and the cholera treatment centre in Beletweyne has been closed. 2016's outbreak was one of the worst and longest in which the country has experienced in the last five years.",
        "interventions": "Humanitarian partners have stepped up response to the outbreak. The CERF rapid response grant of $2 million will strengthen and complement response activities already underway by WASH and Health partners. On 15 March 2017, the Government of Somalia, together with humanitarian partners, launched an Oral Cholera Vaccination campaign, the first of its kind in Somalia, targeting over 450,000 people in seven high-risk areas around the country. WASH partners have furthermore scaled up response to AWD/Cholera, reaching 316,000 people in southern and central Somalia through distribution of hygiene kits, chlorination of water points and hygiene promotion campaigns as of end of February. In total, some 568,600 people were assisted with temporary and/or sustainable access to safe water, 36,000 people with safe sanitation and 498,000 people with hygiene promotion activities.",
        "affected_countries": ["Somalia"],
        "sources": ["OCHA", "WHO", "UNICEF", "Health Cluster", "Gov't"],
        "language": "English"
    }
}

https://reliefweb.int/disaster/ff-2017-0:
